        <p class="research-number">01</p>

        <h2>Epistemology of Machine Learning</h2>

        <p>
          Machine learning has become an increasingly important component
          of scientific research. Across disciplines ranging from climate
          science and biology to physics, machine-learning systems are now
          routinely used to generate predictions, uncover complex patterns,
          and support scientific investigation. Their growing role raises
          fundamental epistemological questions. Under what conditions can
          machine learning contribute to scientific knowledge? What kind of
          understanding can it provide? And how should scientists interpret
          both its successes and its failures?
        </p>

        <p>
          My research examines these questions at the intersection of
          philosophy of science and philosophy of artificial intelligence.
          Rather than asking whether machine learning should replace
          traditional scientific methods, I investigate how it changes
          scientific reasoning itself. This includes the epistemic role of
          machine-learning models, the relation between prediction and
          understanding, and the conditions under which scientists can
          justifiably rely on highly complex systems.
        </p>

        <p>
          A particular focus of my work concerns the epistemic significance
          of predictive failure. While successful machine-learning predictions
          have received increasing philosophical attention, comparatively
          little has been said about situations in which these systems fail
          to meet expectations. I investigate how such failures can reveal
          hidden assumptions, expose limitations in existing theoretical
          frameworks, or point towards previously overlooked features of the
          phenomenon under investigation. In this sense, unsuccessful
          prediction is not simply a methodological setback, but can become
          an important source of scientific understanding.
        </p>

        <p>
          Methodologically, my work combines conceptual analysis with close
          engagement with contemporary machine-learning research and
          scientific case studies. Rather than treating machine learning as
          an abstract philosophical topic, I draw on examples from ongoing
          scientific practice to analyse how these systems contribute to
          scientific inquiry and how traditional epistemological concepts
          should be reconsidered in light of their increasing use.
        </p>
      </div>

    </article>

